<tr id="iconRow">
<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Undercut" class="currentChild" href="Undercut">Undercut</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
On an offset lithographic printing press cylinder (in particular, the <a title="Plate Cylinder" href="Plate_Cylinder">plate cylinder</a> and the <a title="Blanket Cylinder" href="Blanket_Cylinder">blanket cylinder</a>), the difference between the radius of the cylinder's <a title="Bearer" href="Bearer">bearer</a>s (metal rings at each end of the cylinder) and that of the cylinder body itself. The cylinder body—the portion of the cylinder where the plate or blanket is attached—is lower than that of the "true" diameter of the cylinder (indicated by the diameter of the bearer). The cylinder is undercut so as to provide room for plate or blanket <a title="Packing" href="Packing">packing</a>, or adjustments in the height of the plate or blanket. (See <a title="Plate Cylinder" href="Plate_Cylinder">Plate Cylinder</a>, <a title="Blanket Cylinder" href="Blanket_Cylinder">Blanket Cylinder</a>, and <a title="Packing" href="Packing">Packing</a>.) On the press <a title="Impression Cylinder" href="Impression_Cylinder">impression cylinder</a>, it is typically the bearers which are undercut, as the impression cylinder does not require packing. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
In <a title="Cutting and Trimming" href="Cutting_and_Trimming">cutting and trimming</a>, an <em>undercut</em> is a short undesirable cut caused by weak pressure of the <a title="Cutter Clamp" href="Cutter_Clamp">cutter clamp</a>. See <a title="Cutting and Trimming" href="Cutting_and_Trimming">Cutting and Trimming</a>. 
</p>
